tr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF042671%2F1"><gtr:id>998A2586-77FD-4749-9AE2-7937D1E2514D</gtr:id><gtr:title>Trauma and the Political: Rethinking Violence in International Politics</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F042671/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>This project provides a theoretically novel, interdisciplinary re-thinking of approaches to violence and trauma in contemporary politics.&amp;nbsp; Ethical reflection in International Relations is prompted by global suffering, but the suffering that initially prompts this reflection is forgotten in the generalised, rational response.&amp;nbsp; Schick examines and critiques the responses to violence in mainstream and critical international political thought, positing engagement with suffering as the starting point for responsible global politics.&amp;nbsp; She draws on the work of Theodor W. Adorno and Gillian Rose to suggest an alternative way of thinking about and responding to suffering in international political thought, supporting her theoretical argument with historical and sociological sources.&amp;nbsp; These sources suggest that unless traumatic experiences are worked through, they trigger either withdrawal from political engagement or a search for revenge and further violence.&amp;nbsp; Schick advocates mourning and critical reflection in response to trauma and suffering to enable social and political reengagement in life.&amp;nbsp; Such a response looks both to the past and to the future in an attempt to halt the cycles of violence that pervade the international system: understanding and mourning historical and structural antecedents of suffering and engaging in political action to re-shape institutions.&amp;nbsp; 
